author: David Mountain
description: I usually agree with most PragerU Videos but this is overly simplistic. It suggests that it\'s not possible to make a profit while being socially and environmentally responsible. The devil is in the detail, but I can free-range-farm chickens and still turn a profit without torturing birds in the process. You don\'t need to chose one or the other, in fact the only way to save the planet, needs to be a profitable way or people won\'t do it. We do need to stop demonizing people and companies for the wrong reasons though. Oil companies should be a stepping stone to better options but we should be seeking those better options not pretending oil is forever. Elon musk was a good example but you mistook his reasons. He wanted to develop an electric car IN ORDER to save the planet BUT he knew it had to be profitable or it would never happen.

author: boxofrox
description: it has close to never run a profit, but yet it is still around. Soooo.... it still makes a profit? Why would you expect any company, that makes a profit, to fold?  so maybe profit doesn\'t decide if a company is good? My favorite restaurant down the street doesn\'t have fortune 500 profits, so it\'s good from the perspective that I don\'t have to shop/prepare/cook/clean-up a meal when I can afford to eat there. If I\'m investing in stocks for my retirement, (and if the restaurant was publicly traded), I might look elsewhere for a better return on my investment. I might even compare profits (among other things) to determine which company to invest in. The "definition" given in the video at that timestamp is "In capitalism, there is a simple metric for success: how much money you\'re making." I say "definition", because the video is simply stating that profit is a metric, not defining the word. And profit can be used to "simply" compare two companies to make a quick estimation of which is "more" successful. Also, success is not identical to good. You can find successful, yet bad, companies in the top 500. Pick your definition of bad: immoral, unethical, corrupt, unfair, exploits child labor, unsafe working conditions, kicked your dog, shat in your fruit-loops, d) all the above.

author: Derick Hall
description: This is quite a pessimistic outlook. I do believe ESG should not be the primary metric. But I also think this video does not account for a "profit at all cost" mentality that a lot of companies and people have. What if services are inherently immoral or there are incentives, like a degrading society, that would drive people to deliver more socially conscious services? Perhaps a better view to pose against both ESG-only or profit at all cost is a holistic stakeholder focus which includes the triple bottom line, i.e. people, planet, profit. Working in a highly corporate and financial field I realise that as of today it is naive to think people do think this way. However, I do not think it is outside of the realm of belief that mainstream consumers and corporates will change their thinking around weighing ESG forces against profits. Overall, is it not irresponsible to bash ESG like this? To your point on oil, I totally agree, putting pressure on energy companies to become more "green" or shut down right away is perhaps illogical. Take our global dependance on coal as an example: Is coal bad for the environment? Yes. Do the vast majority of developing societies rely on coal? Yes. Here you see the E  S at odds. Now, am I naive to believe that these companies have a responsibility to at least either try to be more efficient or alternatively invest in greener technologies? Not saying current "solutions" e.g. wind is the solution, but are we not at a point as a global society where it seems logical to start looking for ways to find profit while taking ESG into account? I also thoroughly dislike the shoe example, that industry in particular has lead to a lot of grossly underpaid employees and shifting production away from underemployed countries for the sake of profit. Ultimately, why can ESG and profit not both be considerations? Don\'t build a business only for the sake of either, but for both?

author: Harry Binn
description: I believe in Capitalism, but not an unrestrained Capitalization. Under Capitalism many companies moved to China and some other 3rd world Asian nations to maximize profits. However those countries and companies didn\'t seem to worry about labor conditions or environmental impact. On the other hand, forcing everything to meet exacting standards of social justice activists will ensure that nothing gets done. There has to be a middle ground that does both. We\'ve seen the abuse in history of workers from Railroad barons to the work houses of England and the slavery in both the US AND almost every other nation. That\'s not great labor conditions, but it was part of capitalism. James Tour has a video out about flashing carbon into graphene. The benefits of this process would be and are showing to be incredible in the production of products and the recycling of goods; which means less garbage heading to dumps. This is an example of capitalism benefiting others while also ensuring we care of the planet. Add in proper labor conditions and we\'ve met all the criterial.

author: Timothy Wong
description: Not saying I disagree with what was presented, but I believe that ESG could have aided profits for a company. For example, my company who works on building services contracting, recently started a new branch that helps commercial building owners and shopping mall management companies to increase energy efficiency of their air conditioning system, with a whole proposal of payback through reduction in electricity bills down the road. Assuming that the intelligent system my company sells does work (and I do believe it does) and the payback calculation is sound, the investment undertaken by the property owners would eventually generate additional profit, and at the same time enable their company to do business more environmentally friendly. My point is, ESG in itself is not a bad thing for investors, especially those who are looking at long term returns, it is just that the authoritarian and subjective system described in this video had twisted it to serve other motives.

author: Mary Comstock
description: Decades ago when I was studying for my MBA, I subscribed to the then promoted, logical stakeholder theory of business where the considerations of shareholders, suppliers, employees, customers, etc., were valued and worthy of review in order to optimize the efficiency and profitability of your company. Ideally, the more each area was satisfied, the better all functioned to produce quality products at fair price while building profit and reputation. ESG coopts and corrupts this philosophy, costing every stakeholder through an artificial, superfluous, subjective, politically motivated "standard" that immediately looses any credibility since the "standard" is nebulous and open to radical change at any given time. Russ Comstock

author: Paulito Mandia
description: I support capitalism and laissez-faire. But one issue that I have seen is that multinational companies leave first-world countries. Because in those more affluent countries, there are laws that protect the welfare of the laborers, and the minimum wages are high. The reason companies are attracted to third-world countries like the country I live in is that there are less stringent "ESG" guidelines: mining companies can dump toxic wastes with impunity, the minimum wages here are cheap, which unfortunately is less than what is needed for decent living, workers live in cramped quarters, factories displace local wildlife and indigenous people, and so on. Government officials offer little to no resistance because they are bribed by companies. And resisting tribal chieftains are assassinated by bribed officials, to the benefit of the multinationals. In short, imposition of ESG on first-world countries is detrimental to companies, so they move to poorer countries that have low ESG standards, hence they profit, but at the expense of the local population. So how can we reconcile removal of ESG with keeping businesses profitable while still maintaining the dignity of the third-world citizens?

author: Chris Butler
description: A corporation\'s purpose is to make a profit for it\'s stockholders. The corporation has a legal and fiduciary responsibility to obey laws and regulations that apply to its operation. The stockholders can then apply profits they receive to any worthwhile purpose or cause they personally choose. A corporation who uses company funds to boost one cause or another at the whim of management is effectively stealing from the stockholders. Even if some stockholders agree with them, they are unilaterally deciding that their interests or preferences are more important than the people who lend them money to operate. They have no right to force their political/social causes on all the investors.

description: We need to be careful not to throw the "G" baby out with the "ES" bathwater. Disasters like Enron, which harm everyone from consumers to investors to the markets themselves, occur almost without exception due to the failure (or absence) of corporate governance, and are almost inevitably made worse by subsequent attempts by the State to take over that function. The key phrase in the Klaus Schwab quote is "short term profit". When markets are dominated by speculators at the expense of investors, and that behavior is enabled and encouraged by unethical executives, negligent boards, and crony politicians and regulators, everybody loses.

The one thing I would point out though...SHORT TERM profit focus isn\'t the best way to run a company, necessarily; chasing your tail to satisfy the analysts ever quarter can lead to some self-destructive moves...it\'s LONG TERM profit that gets you the best earnings AND is also best for your people and markets because it gives you the stability you need. (It also means that lying, cheating, and doing shady things aren\'t a good idea because they will bite you in the ass in the long term. And again, you CAN easily profit without resorting to any of those.)

author: Wintermute
description: Sorry, but this is definitly not the full truth either. Making a company pay for the external costs it produces, like environmental damage, is absolutely necessary in my opinion. Because if not, in every single case SOMEONE ELSE has to pay for it. Often times our children, the future tax payers. So, when a business which relied on not having to pay for it\'s external costs is now forced to pay for ALL the costs it actually produces, it is only natural that it\'s reported profits and company value will decline. And if under these circumstances the business has to file for bankruptcy, then the business model was already flawed in the first place. This is actually a good thing, because all things considered that particular business NEVER added any value for society. It was only able to survive because someone else was paying some of the bills all the time. If we want capitalism to do good for society, it is necessary that a company value reflects all relevant information about the business. Otherwise, missallocation of capital will be the consequence which will do harm in the long term.

description: I will agree that the profit motive is a driving force behind economic growth, but i believe that compagnies should be hold accountable on the ways they make profit. Their are a hull bunch of methods they use that are highly unethical, like paiement slashs, negligence, faltee equipement, no premium or retirement benefits, paiement below the minimal wage gap, not giving enough hours to their employees when they have the means, child labor in foreign countries, etc, etc. Yes, i know what you\'re thinking, if you don\'t like your job because it dosen\'t treats its employees fairly, find another one, but if all compagnies acted the same way, what would be the point of that? All i\'m saying is, yes, compagnies can and should make profits, but that dosen\'t mean they can do it in anyway they want. I mean, if profit is all that matters, why not legalize slavery? Imagine how much money compagnies would make if they didn\'t have to pay their employees.

But it\'s a fact that employees\' needs can be leveraged by employers to give them worse conditions. author: Issuma
description: I am still not convinced that ESG is a bad idea. Investors want profit, yes, and rightly so, but environmental degradation CAN be a long-term issue even for non-investors, as can certain governance issues (we already have laws against egregious social malfeasance). Of course if an environmental metric is simply wrong--CO2 will kill us all--then such ratings will be counter productive. I would like to see a long interview with an ESG expert who can get into the weeds and point out good and bad potentials in ESG investing. One thing is for certain: ESG is gaining popularity, yet this over-simplification will do nothing to stop the trend. To me the main issue is what metrics are used, and how can profitability be sensibly incorporated into the ESG models.
title: I am still not convinced that ESG is a bad idea. Investors want profit, yes, and rightly so, but environmental degradation CAN be a long-term issue even for non-investors, as can certain governance issues (we already have laws against egregious social malfeasance). author: designbuild
description: I want to reiterate what was said here: - Profit is- for investment purposes- a KPI of success in a mission (optimal delivery of goods and services to those who want / need it). - environmental and social goals would be included in these optimized goods/services rendered (as alluded to in video, profit more adequately shows whether the proper balance of keeping people from freezing in winter is balanced with green initiatives.). ESG runs risk of playing favorites in the market and hurting or killing people en masse. Big tech may carbon neutrally store/move information around, but they can\'t put food on your table. Lastly, this whole trend is really more about the battle of global, monopolistic control vs. local control and responsibilities/direction of culture being shared at all levels of institutions and people. "you will own nothing and you will be happy" is where this is intentionally leading even if some involved in its promotion are \'useful idiots\'.

Pure Capitalism is just as bad as pure Socialism (even worse, pure Communism). You need a perfect balance of Capitalism and Socialism. Each country has it\'s own balance that works. The US has shown the good and the ugly side of Capitalism, just as Russia has done with Communism. Capitalism only works when there is healthy competition in the private market, but causes havoc when a monopoly is involved (due to patents ect). When a monopoly starts, there is nothing stopping that company from asking whatever price they want as government will not get involved. One infamous example is Martin Shkreli who bought the life saving Daraprim HIV drug rights and skyrocketed the price from $13.50 a pill to $750 a pill. A lot of the USA\'s medical bill nightmares people in the US face are a result from this issue.

author: Chad Disrud
description: Part of what is not included in this video is the part of investing where I am a customer choosing my investment product. I used to invest in "blood diamond" businesses which profited from war torn areas and employing child labor to mine diamonds. I chose to change my investment to other international mining companies as I didn\'t want to assist the other companies. It was my choice to change which product I was purchasing. There is good and bad in business. On one hand, inventors and entrepreneurs pursue making products people want in a competitive environment. On the other hand they often will do any unethical, underhanded thing to out compete and destroy their competition so as to become the only supplier of a product while they increase the price of their product. An example is Walmart. It hires people to investigate how it can destroy local competition in local communities after it moves into a town. It then can set whatever price it wants on products as well as lower salaries to the people who work there as it is primarily concerned about the profits of the Sam Walton family and large investors.

But those who suffer the most are the employees and the consumers. The "woke" will blame capitalism for this suffering, but the "woke" are idiots. It\'s the interference with capitalism which causes the suffering.

description: @Ajourneyofknowing 1912 the parties switching doesn\'t really make sense except if you are really ignorant: it\'s not you can identify people who swapped places across the political board. The impression uninformed people have that there might have been a switch is tied to the very notion of being a conservative Vs a progressive: republicans are conservative and they tend to hold on to older values. But, as Hayek said, conservatism is only as good as what it conserves. Sometime in the XXth century some of the conservatives in the US might have clinged to the wrong old values, but today they are mostly upholding values that really made America a superpower: individual rights and freedom above anything else, especially government.

author: Thump Er the Sweaty Fat Guy
description: @ootmaster1 how many vehicles are you flipping and how fast? I am not allowed an income other than the VA or SSDI, but I can sell a car for a profit. I can\'t sell cars as a dealer, but if I get one, fix the small things wrong with it (brake lines and transmissions are the big ones here) I can sell it. I do not live in a city or town because of what I like to do with my spare time... I build muscle cars and 4x4 trucks for fun. I am not running a business, I simply like to do things with vehicles and sometimes sell one. If my crippled ass can do it and remain legal, and not get the VA pissed off at me, you probably can too. They want their taxes, which is why you are supposed to get a dealer license if you are flipping cars, or a fuel permit if you make vodka fuel like I do. If I make fuel and use it on site, no taxes are required to be paid. If I drive my vehicles on Michigan roads with my vodka fuel, also no taxes need to be paid as the fuel is not \'sold\' and the law states the tax is on fuel sold in the state. They get really pissy when they don\'t get their taxes. Its all about the money. Your money and they want it.

description: @DBOYGAMER818 it came from a recent event in NASCAR. While a reporter was interviewing the winning racer, the crowd was chanting "F*ck U, Biden!".
